 AGNES NWORIE, ABAKALIKI NO fewer than 30 persons, mostly males, have been reportedly sent to their early graves by suspected armed Fulani herders in three communities of Ishielu Local Government Area of Ebonyi State. The Point gathered that the victims, who are mostly commercial motorcyclists and travelers, were killed by the armed men, mercilessly, around 7pm on the way from their various businesses. An eyewitness said the attackers, armed with AK-47, numbering about 20, invaded the first community in a lorry. They were said to have hidden inside the lorry unknown to the native dwellers and had planned to unleash mayhem at night. According to the source, some hunters got the hint and attempted foiling their plans by alerting a few natives. Consequently, the armed men reportedly began shooting sporadically at anyone at sight instead of waiting till nightfall. The gunmen allegedly attacked three communities in Íshíelu Local Government Area, namely: Egedege, Obegu and Amazu communities. The number of casualties could not be accurately ascertained as of the time of filing this report. However, many people sustained various degrees of injuries, while vehicles, motorcycles and houses were burnt. The attackers, it was further learnt, also looted some properties from the area. A priest of the Methodist church, whose name could not be ascertained, an artisan, one Mr Okonkwo Agwu, from Umuhuali village, was also among those killed. Agwu was reportedly killed on his way from the day’s work. Chairman of the local government, Sunday Eze, confirmed the incident. The spokesperson for the Police Command, Loveth Odah, also confirmed the attack.  